  "notes": {
    "contrastWithCaseLaw": "Unlike the case law examples (HC 126.292, ADI 4983, IPI), this case has no judicial Interpretive Versions. Every action is a legislative Amendment, and each amendment terminates the prior S-TV before creating the new one. The result is always |V_valid| = 1 — a single, unambiguous text at any query date. This is the baseline scenario that motivated the SAT-Graph model: even without judicial overlays, temporal retrieval must be version-aware.",
    "pointInTime": "The paper's Use Case 1 queries this item at 2001-05-20, which falls within the EC 26/2000 half-open window [2000-02-14, 2010-02-04). The deterministic answer: 'moradia' is a social right; 'alimentação' and 'transporte' are not yet.",
    "topologyInsight": "Legislative amendments follow the superseding model: S-TV_n → Amendment → S-TV_{n+1}. The old S-TV is terminated (terminatesVersionIds is non-empty). This is the opposite of judicial interpretations, which follow the overlay model (terminatesVersionIds: [])."
  }
